{
  "texts": [
    "This paper takes an interdisciplinary approach to the question, combining state-of-the-art knowledge in computational statistics with an original normative argument, drawing mainly from political theory.",
    "We aim to introduce a complex phenomenon to a wide audience, as well as to provide some guidance for both ethical reasoning and future policy-making.",
    "We claim that artificially intelligent polls are potentially desirable for voters in electoral democracies.",
    "We do so by critically engaging with four objections: (1) the privacy objection which is concerned with the harm generated by the collection, storage, and publication of granular data about voting preferences; (2) the autonomy objection, which argues that polls are an obstacle to independently formed judgments; (3) the tactical voting objection, which argues that voting strategically on the basis of polls is worrisome; and finally (4) the manipulation objection, according to which malicious actors could systematically bias predictions to alter voting behaviours.",
    "Instead, we argue the following."
  ]
}